  "answer": "The critic’s objection rests on a misreading of the rubric. The std-hist requirement is that a historical-mechanism account must state forbidden cases—i.e., concrete observations that would falsify the claim. The target does this by providing a single, precisely specified forbidden case: the absence of a significant precipitation drop in high-resolution speleothem and lake-core records for 1200–1150 BC. The rubric’s parenthetical “(plural)” is a descriptive gloss indicating that typically more than one such case is expected, not a rigid numerical minimum of two. A single well-defined forbidden case that is concrete, datable, and realistically obtainable satisfies the core demand of the standard, because it establishes a clear falsification condition. The critic has not demonstrated that the rubric imposes an absolute lower bound of two forbidden cases, nor that the single case provided is insufficient to test the mechanism. Therefore, the target does not violate the explicit requirement."
